{
  "card_id": "mitigation_block",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Mitigation Block",
  "aliases": [
    "OB dragged over",
    "ob dragged over",
    "old order block reused",
    "Old Order Block reused",
    "减伤块"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A mitigation block is a violated order block from the opposite side of the market maker curve, dragged forward to act as a reaccumulation/redistribution zone. It forms when price fails to make a new high/low, creating a low-high-lower low-lower high (bearish) or low-high-higher low-higher high (bullish) structure without sweeping a prior swing high/low. It serves as support/resistance on retest, often overlapping with a fair value gap.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a prior order block (up-close for bullish, down-close for bearish) that has been violated (price closed through it).",
    "For the reversal pattern, identify a sequence: low, high, higher low, higher high (bullish) or high, low, lower high, lower low (bearish), without sweeping an opposite swing high/low like a breaker.",
    "For reaccumulation/redistribution, locate old up-close (bullish) or down-close (bearish) order blocks from the opposing curve that have been violated, then extend them horizontally forward to current price action as a mitigation block.",
    "Confirm the mitigation block by overlap with a fair value gap or other PD array for increased probability.",
    "Validate using SMT divergence: check if a correlated asset has a corresponding breaker or has taken a swing high/low that the mitigation block lacks.",
    "Wait for price to retest the block's open, high, or low before entering; set stop at the opposite end of the block's candle.",
    "In multi-timeframe analysis, lower timeframe mitigation blocks often align with higher timeframe key levels (FVG or order block)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Mitigation blocks act as reversal zones or confluence areas within market maker models. They provide structure-based entries without a prior liquidity sweep. Stronger when overlapping with a fair value gap and confirmed by SMT divergence. Failure of a mitigation block often turns it into a liquidity target. Traders can drop to lower timeframes (e.g., 15s, 1m) to find precise entries using FVG or OTE, targeting higher timeframe objectives.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing mitigation block with breaker block: mitigation does not require sweeping a prior high/low, breaker does.",
    "Trading mitigation blocks without SMT confirmation, leading to failure swings that become liquidity targets.",
    "Entering immediately on the first retest without seeing price reaction or reaccumulation within the block.",
    "Ignoring higher timeframe context and treating all similar sequences as valid mitigation blocks.",
    "Marking a mitigation block before price has actually violated (closed through) the old order block.",
    "Neglecting to look for additional PD arrays (e.g., FVG, volume imbalance) inside the block for precise entry.",
    "Using the wrong side: keeping a buy-side order block on the buy side instead of dragging it to the sell side."
  ],
